citeinfo.title: Phase 1 (Broad Scale) Forest Inventory - Generalized

pubinfo.publish: Alberta Environment and Sustainable Resource Development, Government of Alberta

descript.abstract:
This dataset is produced for the Government of Alberta and is available to the general public. Please consult the Distribution Information of this metadata for the appropriate contact to acquire this dataset.
During and shortly after the Second World War the demand for lumber and wood products increased dramatically. This resulted in concern over lack of knowledge about the extent of the provincial forest resource, and led to fears that the timber supply could be easily depleted. The Phase 1, or Broad Scale, Forest Inventory was initiated in 1949 in response to these concerns. The inventory served as the information base to plan the management of Alberta's forest resource. The Phase 1 (Broad Scale) Forest Inventory included all publicly owned forested lands in the province except Indian lands, national parks and an area known as the Rocky Mountains Forest Reserve. Through aerial photo interpretation, land was classed according to vegetation cover as productive, potentially productive or non-productive.
On productive forest land, stands were classified by cover types, described using crown density, height and tree species. The minimum polygon size was 65 hectares. Potentially productive land included burned or harvested areas and cultivated land. Non-productive lands comprised organic soils, lakes and barren rock. Neither age nor site class was associated with the polygons.
In 1957 a provincial level hard copy map was produced. The cover types were classified (rolled up) into 16 classes:
Class Description 1 Coniferous stands up to 60' (18 m) height 2 Coniferous stands over 60' (18 m) height 3 Mixedwood stands up to 60' (18 m) height 4 Mixedwood stands over 60' (18 m) height 5 Deciduous stands up to 60' (18 m) height 6 Deciduous stands over 60' (18 m) height 7 Burns - 1941 to 1957 inclusive 8 Old burn and brushland 9 Old burn - productive and non-productive 10 Agriculture and other improved lands 11 Muskeg and Marsh 12 Rock barren 14 Barren above timberline 15 Indian Reserves 16 Lakes and Rivers 17 National Park
The Phase 1 (Broad Scale) Forest Inventory generalized data, scanned images, reports, status map and index map are available from Alberta Environment and Sustainable Resource Development, Government of Alberta.
descript.purpose: The Phase 1 (Broad Scale) Forest Inventory (generalized) hardcopy map was converted to digital data to allow comparisons of the historical forest cover with current conditions. The Phase 1 (Broad Scale) Forest Inventory was used to define lands suitable for agriculture, to determine timber harvest levels and plan forest protection and timber and industrial development.
descript.supplinf:
The hardcopy map was digitized in 1996 by the Forest Protection Division, Alberta Environment and Sustainable Resource Development, Government of Alberta.
It should be noted that after the inventory was completed in 1956, no attempts were made to keep the information current.

dataqual.logic: The dataset was checked for geometry errors and multipart polygons were exploded. There are 10309 gaps and 2854 overlaps present in the dataset, which have not been repaired.
dataqual.complete: The data are complete for the extent of the Phase 1 (Broad Scale) Forest Inventory area except for a small area of mapsheet 83I04, which was not digitized. Mapsheet 83G16 was included in the collection of scanned images but does not appear to contain any forest inventory data. The feature class area extends to the provincial boundary but the interpreted area does not include all forested areas.
